<subSubSection id="FFFA652AFFC5FFC36207FE9DFC0A9BA3" pageId="11" pageNumber="381" type="description">
<paragraph id="B75F36A1FFC5FFC36207FE9DFBD89A36" blockId="11.[826,1429,368,1488]" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">
The diseases of phytoseids were recently summarized by Bjornson (2008), 
<bibRefCitation id="D3714B50FFC5FFC365BAFE7EFC4E9FBD" author="Hoy M. A. &amp; Jeyaprakash A." pageId="11" pageNumber="381" pagination="329 - 347" refId="ref15298" refString="Hoy M. A., Jeyaprakash A. 2008 - Natural enemies of mass-reared predatory mites (family Phytoseiidae) used for biological pest control - Exp. Appl. Acarol., 46: 329 - 347. doi: 10.1007 / s 10493 - 008 - 9185 - 3" type="journal article" year="2008">Hoy and Jeyaprakash (2008)</bibRefCitation>
and by 
<bibRefCitation id="D3714B50FFC5FFC362D2FE5BFAEB9FBD" author="Schutte C. &amp; Dicke M." box="[1007,1317,438,462]" pageId="11" pageNumber="381" pagination="307 - 328" refId="ref20635" refString="Schutte C., Dicke M. 2008 - Verified and potential pathogens of predatory mites (Acari: Phytoseiidae) - Exp. Appl. Acarol., 46: 307 - 328. doi: 10.1007 / s 10493 - 008 - 9188 - 0" type="journal article" year="2008">Sch端tte and Dicke (2008)</bibRefCitation>
; data on other 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC5FFC362BAFE34FC029F82" box="[903,972,473,497]" class="Insecta" family="Achilidae" genus="Abas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="383" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">ABAs</taxonomicName>
were unavailable. Microorganisms found on and in various 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC5FFC36552FE11FAC89C67" box="[1135,1286,508,532]" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="11" pageNumber="381" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Phytoseiidae</taxonomicName>
were listed by 
<bibRefCitation id="D3714B50FFC5FFC36262FDF2FB489C44" author="Schutte C. &amp; Dicke M." box="[863,1158,543,567]" pageId="11" pageNumber="381" pagination="307 - 328" refId="ref20635" refString="Schutte C., Dicke M. 2008 - Verified and potential pathogens of predatory mites (Acari: Phytoseiidae) - Exp. Appl. Acarol., 46: 307 - 328. doi: 10.1007 / s 10493 - 008 - 9188 - 0" type="journal article" year="2008">Sch端tte and Dicke (2008)</bibRefCitation>
, but only a few caused any damage, mostly when the predators are un- der stress, as in mass-rearing facilities. The disease factors include the bacterium 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC5FFC365E2FD64FBFA9CB0" authority="Schutte et al." authorityName="Schutte" class="Actinobacteridae" family="Micrococcaceae" genus="Acaricomes" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Actinomycetales" pageId="11" pageNumber="381" phylum="Actinobacteria" rank="species" species="phytoseiuli">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC5FFC365E2FD64FC469CB0" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">Acaricomes phytoseiuli</emphasis>
Sch端tte 
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC5FFC362C4FD41FBFA9CB0" box="[1017,1076,683,707]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">et al.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and several microsporidia. The bacterium, apparently restricted to 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC5FFC36419FD22FC949D79" authorityName="Athias-Henriot" authorityYear="1957" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Phytoseiulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="11" pageNumber="381" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persimilis">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC5FFC36419FD22FC949D79" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">P. persimilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is transmitted via feces and debris, causing reduced fitness. The phytoseiid 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC5FFC36599FCF8FC169D23" authority="(Nesbitt)" baseAuthorityName="Nesbitt" baseAuthorityYear="1951" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Galendromus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="11" pageNumber="381" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="occidentalis">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC5FFC36599FCF8FCA69D23" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">Galendromus occidentalis</emphasis>
(Nesbitt)
</taxonomicName>
(formerly in 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC5FFC36546FCD5FB309D23" authorityName="Muma" authorityYear="1961" box="[1147,1278,824,848]" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Metaseiulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="11" pageNumber="381" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC5FFC36546FCD5FB309D23" box="[1147,1278,824,848]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">Metaseiulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) infected by 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC5FFC36207FCB6FC7E9D00" box="[826,944,859,883]" class="Bacteroidia" family="Amoebophilaceae" genus="Cardinium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Cytophagales" pageId="11" pageNumber="381" phylum="Bacteroidota" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC5FFC36207FCB6FC7E9D00" box="[826,944,859,883]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">Cardinium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a bacterium from the 
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC5FFC36588FCB6FA8F9D00" box="[1205,1345,859,883]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">Bacteroidetes</emphasis>
group, has a shorter life, fewer progeny and a male-biased sex ratio (
<bibRefCitation id="D3714B50FFC5FFC3628BFC4CFB6E9DCA" author="Wu K. &amp; Hoy M. A." box="[950,1184,929,953]" pageId="11" pageNumber="381" pagination="359 - 365" refId="ref22628" refString="Wu K., Hoy M. A. 2012 - Cardinium is associated with reproductive incompatibility in the predatory mite Metaseiulus occidentalis (Acari: Phytoseiidae) - J. Inverteb. Pathol., 10: 359 - 365." type="journal article" year="2012">Wu and Hoy 2012</bibRefCitation>
). The microsporidium 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC5FFC3624EFC29FAF39DAF" authority="Becnel et al." authorityName="Becnel" box="[883,1341,964,988]" class="Microsporea" family="Unikaryonidae" genus="Oligosporidium" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Glugeida" pageId="11" pageNumber="381" phylum="Microsporidia" rank="species" species="occidentalis">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC5FFC3624EFC29FB6A9DAF" box="[883,1188,964,988]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">Oligosporidium occidentalis</emphasis>
Becnel 
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC5FFC36438FC28FAF39DAF" box="[1285,1341,964,988]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">et al.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shortens the life of 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC5FFC362C1FC0AFB6F9D8C" box="[1020,1185,999,1023]" class="Microsporea" family="Unikaryonidae" genus="Oligosporidium" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Glugeida" pageId="11" pageNumber="381" phylum="Microsporidia" rank="species" species="occidentalis">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC5FFC362C1FC0AFB6F9D8C" box="[1020,1185,999,1023]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">G. occidentalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, reduces its fecundity and causes a male-biased sex ratio (
<bibRefCitation id="D3714B50FFC5FFC36414FBE7FBC59A36" author="Hoy M. A. &amp; Jeyaprakash A." pageId="11" pageNumber="381" pagination="329 - 347" refId="ref15298" refString="Hoy M. A., Jeyaprakash A. 2008 - Natural enemies of mass-reared predatory mites (family Phytoseiidae) used for biological pest control - Exp. Appl. Acarol., 46: 329 - 347. doi: 10.1007 / s 10493 - 008 - 9185 - 3" type="journal article" year="2008">Hoy and Jeyaprakash 2008</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B75F36A1FFC5FFC3625DFBB7FC0A9BA3" blockId="11.[826,1429,368,1488]" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">
Only few viruses were detected in the 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC5FFC36463FBB7FC6D9AE6" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="11" pageNumber="381" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Phytoseiidae</taxonomicName>
and their negative effects are unknown (
<bibRefCitation id="D3714B50FFC5FFC3627FFB4DFB919ACB" author="Schutte C. &amp; Dicke M." box="[834,1119,1184,1208]" pageId="11" pageNumber="381" pagination="307 - 328" refId="ref20635" refString="Schutte C., Dicke M. 2008 - Verified and potential pathogens of predatory mites (Acari: Phytoseiidae) - Exp. Appl. Acarol., 46: 307 - 328. doi: 10.1007 / s 10493 - 008 - 9188 - 0" type="journal article" year="2008">Sch端tte and Dicke 2008</bibRefCitation>
). There are also a few reports of diseases affecting 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC5FFC36552FB2EFB7A9AA8" box="[1135,1204,1219,1243]" class="Insecta" family="Achilidae" genus="Abas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="383" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">ABAs</taxonomicName>
in the field, e.g. an infection of 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC5FFC362F7FB0AFB5E9A8D" authorityName="Denmark &amp; Muma" authorityYear="1970" box="[970,1168,1254,1278]" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Euseius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="11" pageNumber="381" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="citrifolius">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC5FFC362F7FB0AFB5E9A8D" box="[970,1168,1254,1278]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">Euseius citrifolius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<collectingCountry id="CFF77631FFC5FFC365A4FB0BFAC69A8D" box="[1177,1288,1254,1278]" name="Denmark" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">Denmark</collectingCountry>
and Muma by the fungus 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC5FFC362D0FAE7FB409B52" box="[1005,1166,1290,1313]" class="Entomophthoromycetes" family="Neozygitaceae" genus="Neozygites" kingdom="Fungi" order="Entomophthorales" pageId="11" pageNumber="381" phylum="Entomophthoromycota" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC5FFC362D0FAE7FBAD9B52" box="[1005,1123,1290,1313]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">Neozygites</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry id="CFF77631FFC5FFC365FFFAE4FAC99B52" box="[1218,1287,1289,1313]" name="Brazil" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="D3714B50FFC5FFC36424FAE4FC549B37" author="Furtado I. P. &amp; de Moraes G. J. &amp; Keller A." pageId="11" pageNumber="381" pagination="85 - 86" refId="ref13795" refString="Furtado I. P., de Moraes G. J., Keller A. 1996 - Infection of Euseius citrifolius (Acari: Phytoseiidae) by an entomophthralean fungus in Brazil - Rev. Ecossistema, 21: 85 - 86." type="journal article" year="1996">
Furtado 
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC5FFC364BCFAE7FC9A9B37" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="381">et al.</emphasis>
1996
</bibRefCitation>
). The presence of potential disease factors on and in 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC5FFC36286FAA2FBCE9B14" box="[955,1024,1359,1383]" class="Insecta" family="Achilidae" genus="Abas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="383" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">ABAs</taxonomicName>
in the field may become a problem when they are brought into the laboratory to be mass-reared; requiring screening and sanitation procedures.
</paragraph>
